In an age where new video games can range from two-hour indie gems to sprawling 100-hour epics, should players expect every critic to experience one hundred percent of what the game offers before delivering an opinion. In today's fast paced and ever-expanding landscape of gaming, critics are often forced to operate under tight deadlines. The pressure to publish reviews before a game’s release means that many reviewers barely scratch the surface of the gameplay or story.  
While many publishers provide early review copies to allow critics more time to complete games, this system isn’t without its flaws. Recent controversies, such as those surrounding [Dragon Age: The Veilguard](LINK PLS), highlight the issues inherent in pre-release reviews.

## The problem: Are Gamers Getting Incomplete Critiques?
Take for example, the recent reviews for the game *Gran Turismo 7*, [which launched with a very good 87 Metascore](https://www.metacritic.com/game/gran-turismo-7/),  a compilation of multiple reviewers on the popular gaming forum metacritic. However, after its launch, the user score plummeted to a dismal 2.7. This dramatic drop was attributed to hidden post-launch features—issues not covered in initial reviews. These included egregiously grindy progression systems designed to push players toward microtransactions.. Many of these reviewers on this forum did not continue to play the game after the short single player campaign, which is where the game's glaring issues became an issue. This led to the game’s long-term gameplay, the arcade/race modes, which most players spend the majority of their time, unreviewed.   

![Gran Turismo® 7][image1]  
*Pictured: Gran Turismo 7 promotional image*  
The opposite of this issue is also a problem. There are many games out where the main story takes a backseat and it is the side activities and quests that are the largest pull of the game, such as *Skyrim* or *Cyberpunk 2077*. In these games, while they may have wonderful stories, many players agree it is the exploration and activities outside of the main stories that create the adventure. With the time crunch put on reviewers, they are incentivised to skip this side content and rush the end of the main story, skipping the side content that defines the core experience for many players. This practice once again results in incomplete critiques that fail to capture the full scope of such games. 

## When is a game truly “finished”?
What defines when a game is finished? Is it when the credits roll? When the hardest boss is defeated? When you have completed 100% of the achievements? This answer will change from game to game as well as from player to player.  
For games like *Diablo 4,* [the main story runs for a very respectable 25 hours on average](https://howlongtobeat.com/game/71960), but with the completion of all games content, the game runs to a staggering 188 hours. This leads to about a total of 150 hours of content that the majority of reviewers would not touch and thus not review. Though not all reviewers avoid all content in a game.   

![][image2]  
*Pictured: Diablo 4 Promotional Image*   

Some reviewers try to break against this mold though. Mortismal Gaming, a mid-sized YouTube reviewer, is known for completing 100% of a game—including all achievements—before publishing reviews. He reviews many kinds of games, but mainly does large RPG games, such as *Baldur's Gate 3*. [This creates a problem, as these large games take upwards of 170 hours to complete all the content, not including achievements](https://howlongtobeat.com/game/68033). Even with early access, this means Mortismal’s reviews take a month or more to produce. These detailed, hour-long reviews can be incredibly informative but are often released long after a game’s launch, when the initial hype has faded.  

![][image3]  
*Pictured: Baldur's Gate 3 Promotional Image*  

## What is there to do?
## Wait. 
This is the main advice for those concerned about incomplete or misleading reviews. Avoid purchasing games based solely on early reviews. As discussed in other blog posts, these reviews can be very misleading, and sometimes reviewers are either not skilled enough or don't get deep enough into a game to give a complete review.   
Instead, wait for user reviews and feedback to emerge. Communities often uncover issues and features that critics overlook. Additionally, seek out reviewers like Mortismal, who publish in-depth reviews after completing games in their entirety. While these reviews take time, they provide a comprehensive view that early impressions simply cannot.
